--- title: "Challenge 5 Solutions" author: "Meredith Rolfe" description: "Introduction to Visualization" date: "08/23/2022" format: html: df-print: paged toc: false code-copy: true code-tools: true css: styles.css categories: - challenge_5 - railroads - cereal - air_bnb - pathogen_cost - australian_marriage - public_schools - usa_hh --- ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} library(tidyverse) library(ggplot2) knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE) ``` ::: ## Challenge Overview Today's challenge is to: 1) read, clean, and tidy data and then... 2) create at least two univariate visualizations - try to make them "publication" ready - Explain why you choose the specific graph type 3) Create at least one bivariate visualization - try to make them "publication" ready - Explain why you choose the specific graph type There is even an [R Graph Gallery book](https://bookdown.org/content/b298e479-b1ab-49fa-b83d-a57c2b034d49/) to use that summarizes information from the website! :::{.panel-tabset} ## cereal ⭐ The cereal dataset includes sodium and sugar content for 20 popular cereals, along with an indicator of cereal category (A, B, or C) but we are not sure what that variable corresponds to. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} cereal<-read_csv("_data/cereal.csv") ``` ::: ### Univariate Visualizations I am interested in the distribution of sodium and sugar content in cereals, lets start by checking out a simple histogram - binned into approximately 25 mg ranges. I do this by setting bins equal to max minur min of the variable, or 14 bins. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(cereal, aes(x=Sodium)) + geom_histogram(bins=14) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-3-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: It looks like there are some outliers while most cereals are more clumped together between 100 and 200 mg. Unfortunately, we can't automatically label outliers, but there is [a commonly used trick to add in labels ](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/33524669/labeling-outliers-of-boxplots-in-r) that I can never get to work for a single boxplot. So, I use it for grouped data in the example below, but am cheating by using the `car` package to label the outliers for the single boxplot - maybe one of you can find a better way! ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} car::Boxplot(cereal$Sodium, data=cereal, id=list(labels=cereal$Cereal), cex=0.2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-error} ``` Error in loadNamespace(x): there is no package called 'car' ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} is_outlier <- function(x) { return(x < quantile(x, 0.25) - 1.5 * IQR(x) | x > quantile(x, 0.75) + 1.5 * IQR(x)) } cereal %>% mutate(Sugar = Sugar * 15) %>% pivot_longer(cols=c(Sodium, Sugar), names_to = "content", values_to = "value")%>% group_by(content)%>% mutate(outlier = if_else(is_outlier(value), Cereal, NA_character_)) %>% ggplot(., aes(x = content, y = value, color=factor(content))) + geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) + theme(legend.position = "none") + geom_text(aes(label = outlier), na.rm = TRUE, show.legend = FALSE) + scale_y_continuous("Milligrams (Sodium)", sec.axis = sec_axis(~ . /15, name = "Milligrams (Sugar)") ) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-4-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: How about sugar? We can set the number of bins to cover 2 grams of sugar, or 9. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(cereal, aes(x=Sugar)) + geom_histogram(bins=9) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-5-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: It looks like cereals are more closely grouped with respect to sugar content - and a boxplot indicates no true outliers. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(cereal, aes(y = Sugar)) + geom_boxplot() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-6-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: ### Bivariate Visualization(s) Are cereals high in sodium low in sugar, or vice versa? To answer this question, lets check out a scatterplot. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(cereal, aes(y=Sugar, x=Sodium)) + geom_point() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-7-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: It doesn't look like there is a systematic relationship. However, this might be different if we added in the types A and C. Also, Raisin Bran seems to be high in both! ## pathogen cost ⭐ This dataset includes the total number of cases and total estimated cost for the top 15 pathogens in 2018. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} pathogen<-readxl::read_excel( "_data/Total_cost_for_top_15_pathogens_2018.xlsx", skip=5, n_max=16, col_names = c("pathogens", "Cases", "Cost")) pathogen ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
````` ::: ::: ### Univariate Visualizations Lets check out the distribution of cost and number of cases. There are only 15 observations - even fewer than the number of cereals, and the data are highly skewed. Will the same sorts of visualizations work? ::: {.cell layout-nrow="2"} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(pathogen, aes(x=Cases)) + geom_histogram() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![Histogram of Cases](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-9-1.png){width=672} ::: ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(pathogen, aes(x=Cases)) + geom_histogram()+ scale_x_continuous(trans = "log10") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![Histogram of (Logged) Cases](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-9-2.png){width=672} ::: ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(pathogen, aes(x=Cases)) + geom_boxplot() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![Boxplot of Cases](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-9-3.png){width=672} ::: ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(pathogen, aes(x=Cases)) + geom_boxplot()+ scale_x_continuous(trans = "log10") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![Boxplot of (Logged) Cases](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-9-4.png){width=672} ::: ::: The histogram isn't ideal, we can see the single outlier - but it is hard to get a grasp on the number of cases of pathogens with lower case counts. Perhaps if we rescaled the number of cases to a log or some other scaling function. As we see below, the logging of the x axis is much more revealing. What happens when we graph costs? ::: {.cell layout-ncol="2"} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(pathogen, aes(x=Cost)) + geom_histogram() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![Histogram of Cost](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-10-1.png){width=672} ::: ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(pathogen, aes(x=Cost)) + geom_histogram()+ scale_x_continuous(trans = "log10") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![Histogram of (Logged) Cost](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-10-2.png){width=672} ::: ::: ### Bivariate Visualization(s) Given what we saw above, lets try a logged and unlogged scatterplot for Cases vs Costs. ::: {.cell .column-screen-inset layout-ncol="2"} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(pathogen, aes(x=Cases, y=Cost, label=pathogens)) + geom_point() + scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::comma)+ geom_text() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![Relationship between Cases and Total Cost of Pathogens](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-11-1.png){width=672} ::: ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(pathogen, aes(x=Cases, y=Cost, label=pathogens)) + geom_point()+ scale_x_continuous(trans = "log10", labels = scales::comma)+ scale_y_continuous(trans = "log10", labels = scales::comma)+ ggrepel::geom_label_repel() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![Logged Relationship between Cases and Total Cost](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-11-2.png){width=672} ::: ::: ## Australian Marriage ⭐⭐ In 2017, Australia conducted a postal survey to gauge citizens' opinions towards same sex marriage: "Should the law be changed to allow same-sex couples to marry?" The table provided by the [Australian Bureau of Statistics](https://www.abs.gov.au/) includes estimates of the proportion of citizens choosing to 1) vote yes, 2) vote no, 3) vote in an unclear way, or 4) fail to vote. These results are aggregated by Federal Electoral District, which are nested within one of 8 overarching Electoral Divisions. See Challenge 3 for more details. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} vote_orig <- readxl::read_excel("_data/australian_marriage_law_postal_survey_2017_-_response_final.xls", sheet="Table 2", skip=7, col_names = c("District", "Yes", "del", "No", rep("del", 6), "Illegible", "del", "No Response", rep("del", 3)))%>% select(!starts_with("del"))%>% drop_na(District)%>% filter(!str_detect(District, "(Total)"))%>% filter(!str_starts(District, "\\(")) vote<- vote_orig%>% mutate(Division = case_when( str_ends(District, "Divisions") ~ District, TRUE ~ NA_character_ ))%>% fill(Division, .direction = "down") vote<- filter(vote,!str_detect(District, "Division|Australia")) vote_long <- vote%>% pivot_longer( cols = Yes:`No Response`, names_to = "Response", values_to = "Count" ) ``` ::: ### Univariate Visualization(s) I think I will start out by graphing the overall proportion of Australian citizens who voted yes, no, etc. That requires me to recreate the proportions information we discarded when we read in the data! ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} vote_long%>% group_by(Response)%>% summarise(Count = sum(Count))%>% ggplot(., aes(x=Response, y=Count))+ geom_bar(stat="identity") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-13-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: Hm, I see a few issues. I would like to reorder the Yes and No folks (who voted) and clearly distinguish them from No Response. Plus maybe label the bars with the % vote (or total numbers?) and the axis with the other value. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} vote_long%>% mutate(Response = as_factor(Response), Response = fct_relevel(Response, "Yes", "No", "Illegible"))%>% group_by(Response)%>% summarise(Count = sum(Count))%>% ungroup()%>% mutate(perc = Count/sum(Count))%>% ggplot(., aes(y=perc, x=Response))+ geom_bar(stat="Identity", alpha=.75) + scale_y_continuous(name= "Percent of Citizens", label = scales::percent) + geom_text(aes(label = Count), size=3, vjust=-.5) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](challenge5_solutions_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-14-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: ### Bivariate Visualization(s) ## AB_NYC_2019.csv ⭐⭐⭐ This is a new data set from air bnb, lets check it out. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} airb<-read_csv("_data/AB_NYC_2019.csv") print(summarytools::dfSummary(airb, varnumbers = FALSE, plain.ascii = FALSE, style = "grid", graph.magnif = 0.70, valid.col = FALSE), method = 'render', table.classes = 'table-condensed') ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}

``` ::: ::: ### Univariate Visualizations ### Bivariate Visualization(s) ## Railroads ⭐⭐⭐ The railroad data contain 2931 county-level aggregated counts of the number of railroad employees in 2012. Counties are embedded within States, and all 50 states plus Canada, overseas addresses in Asia and Europe, and Washington, DC are represented. See challenges 1 and 2 for more information. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} railroad<-readxl::read_excel("_data/StateCounty2012.xls", skip = 4, col_names= c("state", "delete", "county", "delete", "employees"))%>% select(!contains("delete"))%>% filter(!str_detect(state, "Total")) railroad<-head(railroad, -2)%>% mutate(county = ifelse(state=="CANADA", "CANADA", county)) ``` ::: Lets create some numerical variables that we can visualize! ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} railroad<- railroad%>% group_by(state)%>% mutate(state_employees = sum(employees), state_countries = n_distinct(county)) ``` ::: ### Univariate Visualizations ### Bivariate Visualization(s) ## Public School Characteristics ⭐⭐⭐⭐ This is another new dataset. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} schools<-read_csv("_data/Public_School_Characteristics_2017-18.csv") print(summarytools::dfSummary(schools, varnumbers = FALSE, plain.ascii = FALSE, style = "grid", graph.magnif = 0.70, valid.col = FALSE), method = 'render', table.classes = 'table-condensed') ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
